\chapter{A toy example}\label{ch:toyexample}
Chapter \ref{ch:wasserstein} introduced Wasserstein and sliced Wasserstein distances.
Chapter \ref{ch:gpr} showed how kernels can be derived from these distances
and explained how these kernels can be used in predictive
modelling, specifically in Gaussian process regression.
In this chapter, I illustrate how these tools can be put into practice.
I do so by means of a toy example constructed specially to demonstrate
the usefulness of sliced Wasserstein kernels in a situation where both
standard vector-based approaches and Wasserstein kernels fail abjectly.

\section{Set-up}
\paragraph{Input distributions.}
For each $a > 0$, we define the bivariate Gaussian mixture distribution
\[
  P(a) := \frac{1}{4}\sum_{i=1}^4 \mathcal{N}_2(\vect \mu_i, \mat I_2),
\]
where
\[
  \vect \mu_1 = \begin{pmatrix}a \\ 0\end{pmatrix},
  ~~~ \vect \mu_2 = \begin{pmatrix}0 \\ a\end{pmatrix},
  ~~~ \vect \mu_3 = -\vect \mu_1,
  ~~~ \vect \mu_4 = -\vect \mu_2.
\]
For each $\omega \in \R$, we further define
\[
  P(a, \omega) := \mathcal{L}(\mat R(\omega)\vect X),
\]
where 
\[
  \mat R(\omega) = \begin{pmatrix}\cos \omega & - \sin \omega \\ \sin \omega & \cos \omega\end{pmatrix}
\]
and $\vect X \sim P(a)$.
That is, $P(a, \omega)$ takes the Gaussian mixture $P(a)$
and rotates it counterclockwise by an angle of $\omega$;
see Figure \vref{fig:toyexample}.
For $\vect Z \sim \mathcal{N}_2(\vect \mu_i, \mat I_2)$,
the random vector $\mat R(\pi/2) \vect Z$ has the distribution
$\mathcal{N}_2(\vect \mu_{i + 1 \mod 4}, \mat I_2), i = 1, \dots, 4$.
The angle $\pi/2$ is the smallest positive angle for which this is true.
As a result, the period of $\omega \mapsto P(a, \omega)$ is $\pi/2$.


<<echo=FALSE, fig.align = "center", fig.height = 3.5, out.width = "\\textwidth", fig.cap = "For this toy example, the data are generated from Gaussian mixture distributions whose components are laid out symmetrically around the origin. The $a$ parameter (here $a = 5$) governs the distance of the component centroids from the origin; the $\\omega$ parameter ($\\omega = \\pi/3$ in the right panel) determines the rotation applied to the unrotated mixture $P(a, 0)$. The ellipses represent 95\\% probability contours of each mixture component, the centroids of which are marked by crosses.\\label{fig:toyexample}", message = FALSE, warning = FALSE>>=
library(ellipse)

a <- 5
Sigma <- diag(0.8, 2)
mus_base <- cbind(c(a, 0), c(0, a), c(-a, 0), c(0, -a))
cols <- c("#1b9e77", "#d95f02", "#7570b3", "#e7298a")

rotate <- function(angle) {
  rbind(c(cos(angle), -sin(angle)),
        c(sin(angle),  cos(angle)))
}

plot_ellipses <- function(angle, title, show_arrow = FALSE) {
  R <- rotate(angle)
  mus <- t(R %*% mus_base)
  Sigma_rot <- R %*% Sigma %*% t(R)
  
  plot(NULL, asp = 1, xlim = c(-8, 8), ylim = c(-8, 8),
       xlab = expression(x[1]), ylab = expression(x[2]),
       main = title)
  abline(h = 0, v = 0, col = "grey85", lty = 2)
  
  for (i in 1:4) {
    e <- ellipse(Sigma_rot, centre = mus[i, ], level = 0.95)
    polygon(e, col = adjustcolor(cols[i], alpha.f = 0.2),
            border = cols[i], lwd = 1.5)
    points(mus[i, 1], mus[i, 2], pch = 3, col = cols[i], cex = 1.2, lwd = 2)
  }
  
  if (show_arrow) {
    # Draw arc around origin from angle 0 to pi/3, at radius r
    r <- a
    arc_angles <- seq(0, angle, length.out = 100)
    arc_x <- r * cos(arc_angles)
    arc_y <- r * sin(arc_angles)
    lines(arc_x, arc_y, col = "grey30", lwd = 1.5)
    
    # Arrowhead at the end of the arc
    end_angle <- angle
    tip_x <- r * cos(end_angle)
    tip_y <- r * sin(end_angle)
    # Direction tangent to arc at end
    tan_x <- -sin(end_angle)
    tan_y <-  cos(end_angle)
    arr_len <- 0.4
    arrows(
      tip_x - arr_len * tan_x,
      tip_y - arr_len * tan_y,
      tip_x, tip_y,
      length = 0.12, angle = 20,
      col = "grey30", lwd = 1.5
    )
  
    # Label: place it just outside the arc, at the midpoint angle
    mid_angle <- angle/2
    label_r <- r + 0.7
    text(label_r * cos(mid_angle), label_r * sin(mid_angle),
         labels = expression(omega == pi/3),
         col = "grey30", cex = 0.95, adj = c(0, 0.5))
  }
}

par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(4, 4, 3, 1), las = 1,
    bty = "n")
plot_ellipses(0,    expression(paste(P(5, 0))))
plot_ellipses(pi/3, expression(paste(P(5, pi/3))),
              show_arrow = TRUE)
@

For any $a, \omega$, 
the expectation of $\vect X \sim P(a, \omega)$ is the zero vector in $\R^2$.
Further, the distribution $P(a, 0)$ is symmetrical about both cardinal axes.
Hence, for $\vect X = (X_1, X_2) \sim P(a, 0)$,
\[
  (X_1, X_2) \eqd (X_1, -X_2),
\]
so
\[
  \Cov(X_1, X_2) = \Cov(X_1, -X_2) = -\Cov(X_1, X_2),
\]
which means that $\Cov(\vect X)$ is diagonal.
Since the first and second component are exchangeable, the diagonal entries
of the covariance matrix are identical.
Along one axis, 
the variance of the mixture is the sum of within- and between-cluster variances, 
i.e., $a^2 + 1$.
Hence, the covariance matrix of $P(a, 0)$ is $(a^2 + 1)\mat I_2$.
The covariance matrix of $P(a, \omega)$ has the same form:
\[
  \mat R(\omega) (a^2 + 1)\mat I_2 \mat R(\omega)\T = (a^2 + 1) \mat R(\omega) \mat R(\omega)\T= (a^2 + 1)\mat I_2.
\]
The first and second moments of $P(a, \omega)$, then, do not depend on $\omega$,
and the first moment does not depend on $a$, either.
Consequently, any vector-based model that uses these moments
will not be useful for predicting the rotation angle $\omega$ in test data.

Let us now turn our attention to the marginal distributions of $(X_1, X_2) \sim P(a, \pi/4 + \omega)$.
The projection of the first mixture component onto the $x$-axis is a normal distribution
with expectation $a \cos (\pi/4 + \omega)$ and unit variance;
the projection of the fourth mixture component onto the $x$-axis is again normal with unit variance,
but with expectation $a \sin (\pi/4 + \omega)$.
By symmetry, we find that the distribution of $X_1$ is
\begin{align*}
  \mathcal{L}(X_1) &= \frac{1}{4}
    \Bigl(
      \mathcal{N}(a \cos (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) +
      \mathcal{N}(-a \sin (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) + \\
      & ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \mathcal{N}(-a \cos (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) +
      \mathcal{N}(a \sin (\pi/4 + \omega), 1)
    \Bigl).
\end{align*}
Similarly, for $(Y_1, Y_2) \sim P(a, \pi/4 -\omega)$,
we obtain
\begin{align*}
  \mathcal{L}(Y_1) 
  &= \frac{1}{4}
    \Bigl(
      \mathcal{N}(a \cos (\pi/4 - \omega), 1) +
      \mathcal{N}(-a \sin (\pi/4 - \omega), 1) + \\
      & ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \mathcal{N}(-a \cos (\pi/4 - \omega), 1) +
      \mathcal{N}(a \sin (\pi/4 - \omega), 1)
    \Bigl) \\
  &= \frac{1}{4}
    \Bigl(
      \mathcal{N}(a \sin (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) +
      \mathcal{N}(-a \cos (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) + \\
      & ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \mathcal{N}(-a \sin (\pi/4 + \omega), 1) + 
      \mathcal{N}(-a \cos (\pi/4 + \omega), 1)
    \Bigl) \\
  &= \mathcal{L}(X_1).
\end{align*}
By the same token, $\mathcal{L}(X_2) = \mathcal{L}(Y_2)$.
Thus, any method relying solely on the marginal distributions of the
input distributions will not be able to tell
$P(a, \pi/4 + \omega)$ and $P(a, \pi/4 - \omega)$ apart.

\paragraph{Scenarios.}
We consider an artificial setting in which we observe
empirical distributions $\widehat P_1, \dots,$ $\widehat P_{N_1+N_2}$
obtained from simple random samples from the distributions
$P(a, \omega_1), \dots, P(a, \omega_{N_1+N_2})$.
The rotation angles $\omega_{1}, \dots, \omega_{N_1}$ with which the training data
were generated are known; 
the objective is to retrieve the values of $\omega_{N_1+1}, \dots, \omega_{N_1 + N_2}$
that were used to generate the test set, which are unknown.
Each sample contains the same number of observations, $n$.

The utility of sliced Wasserstein kernels will be illustrated in two scenarios.
\begin{itemize}
  \item In Scenario 1, the rotation angles are drawn independently 
  from a uniform distribution over the interval $(0, \pi/4)$.
  Over this interval, the images of $\cos$ and $\sin$ do not overlap.
  As a result, 
  the mappings from the rotation angle to the marginal distributions of $P(a, \omega)$
  are injective over this fairly narrow interval,
  and Wasserstein kernels are expected to perform relatively well.

  \item In Scenario 2, the rotation angles are drawn from a uniform distribution 
  over the interval $(0, \pi/2)$.
  While the mapping $\omega \mapsto P(a, \omega)$ is injective over this wider interval,
  the mappings from the rotation angle to the marginal distributions of $P(a, \omega)$ are not.
  Consequently, Wasserstein kernels are expected to show degraded performance,
  whereas sliced Wasserstein kernels, which take into account the whole distribution,
  are still expected to retain some predictive power.
\end{itemize}

In both scenarios, I set $a = 5, N_1 = N_2 = 50$ and $n = 200$.
The values of $\omega_1, \dots, \omega_{N_1 + N_2}$ were sampled independently
from $\textrm{Uniform}(0, \pi/4)$ (Scenario 1) and $\textrm{Uniform}(0, \pi/2)$ (Scenario 2).
For both scenarios, twenty independent realisations of
the rotation angles and the corresponding samples are generated.
Each of the resulting twenty data sets per scenario is analysed independently of the others.

\section{Method of analysis}
For each of the twenty data sets per scenario,
the closeness of the predicted outcomes $\widehat \omega_{N_1 + 1}, \dots,$ 
$\widehat \omega_{N_1 + N_2}$ 
to the test data $\omega_{N_1 + 1}, \dots, \omega_{N_1 + N_2}$  is assessed 
quantitatively by means of the root mean squared error (\textsc{rmse})
\[
  \textsc{rmse}
  := \sqrt{\frac{1}{N_2}\sum_{i = N_1 + 1}^{N_1 + N_2} (\widehat \omega_i - \omega_i)^2}.
\]
The range of the outcomes varies between the two scenarios.
In order to present the results in a more directly comparable fashion,
an $R^2$ value is computed as
\[
  R^2
  := 1 - \frac{\sum_{i = N_1 + 1}^{N_1 + N_2} (\widehat \omega_i - \omega_i)^2}{\sum_{i = N_1 + 1}^{N_1 + N_2} (\overline \omega - \omega_i)^2},
\]
where $\overline \omega = N_1^{-1}\sum_{j=1}^{N_1} \omega_j$ is the mean outcome in the training data.
Higher $R^2$ values correspond to greater predictive accuracy.
This definition allows $R^2$ to be negative when the predictions
are worse than when simply using the training set mean.

\paragraph{Baselines.} 
A reference baseline is established by setting 
$\widehat \omega_i$ to $\overline \omega = N_1^{-1}\sum_{j=1}^{N_1} \omega_j$,
the mean outcome in the training set, $i = N_1+1,\dots, N_1+N_2$.
By definition, the $R^2$ value for this reference baseline is $0$.

While we have established that there is no signal of the outcome
in the means and covariances of the input distributions,
I nonetheless applied a vector-based method to this regression problem
in which each input distribution was summarised by 
the sample means and sample covariances of its first and second dimensions
as well as by the Pearson correlation between its first and second dimensions.
For each distribution, this five-dimensional vector was used as a predictor
in a random forest model \citep[see][]{Breiman2001}.
This model's \texttt{mtry} hyperparameter was tuned by minimising 
the out-of-bag mean squared error over the set $\{1, \dots, 5\}$.
The \texttt{ntree} hyperparameter, 
which rarely substantially affects the performance of random forests, was set to 500.

\paragraph{Wasserstein kernels.} 
Next, a number of Gaussian process models were fitted to the data.
The first two of these models were based on Wasserstein kernels 
(see Definition \vref{def:wassersteinkernel})
for which the inputs were the first and second marginals
of the empirical distributions.
That is, for each pair of empirical input distributions 
$\widehat P(a, \omega_i), \widehat P(a, \omega_j)$,
I computed
\[
  k_W({\vect e_1}_{\#}^{\star}\widehat P(a, \omega_i), {\vect e_1}_{\#}^{\star}\widehat P(a, \omega_j))
\]
and
\[
  k_W({\vect e_2}_{\#}^{\star}\widehat P(a, \omega_i), {\vect e_2}_{\#}^{\star}\widehat P(a, \omega_j)),
\]
where $\vect e_1 = (1, 0)\T$ and $\vect e_2 = (0, 1)\T$.

The hyperparameters $s^2, t$ and $\eta^2$ were tuned by
minimising the negative log-marginal likelihood using the 
\textsc{bfgs} algorithm as described in Section \ref{sec:tuning}.
The hyperparameter search was initialised ten different times in order to
prevent the optimisation algorithm from being stuck near a local minimum.

\paragraph{Sum of Wasserstein kernels.} 
For each pair of empirical input distributions $\widehat P(a, \omega_i), \widehat P(a, \omega_j)$,
I computed the kernel value
\[
  k(\widehat P(a, \omega_i), \widehat P(a, \omega_j); \vect e_1, \vect e_2),
\]
see Definition \vref{def:sumofkernels}.
This kernel combines the information from both marginals into a single kernel, 
potentially allowing the model to use both projection directions simultaneously.
The kernel was used in another Gaussian process model,
whose hyperparameters $s^2_1, s^2_2, t_1, t_2$ and $\eta^2$ were
tuned as explained in Remark \ref{remark:sumofkernels_hyperparameters}.

\paragraph{Sliced Wasserstein kernel.} 
Finally, a Gaussian process model using the sliced Wasserstein kernel 
(Definition \vref{def:slicedwassersteinkernel}) was fitted to the data.
This kernel was estimated using Monte Carlo simulation based
on $L = 50$ projection directions sampled i.i.d.\ from a uniform distribution
over $\Sphere^1$.
For each of the twenty data sets, the projection directions were sampled anew.
The hyperparameters $s^2, t$ and $\eta^2$ were again tuned
by minimising the negative log-marginal likelihood, and, again,
the \textsc{bfgs} algorithm was initialised ten different times for each 
hyperparameter search.

\section{Results}
Table \ref{tab:results_toyexample1} and Figure \ref{fig:results_toyexample1}
show the \textsc{rmse} values achieved by each modelling approach
in the scenario in which the rotation angles were sampled from a uniform
distribution over the interval $(0, \pi/4)$.
As expected, the three Wasserstein kernels substantially outperform both the naïve
baseline and the random forest baseline.
However, they are themselves outperformed by the sliced Wasserstein kernel.
This suggests that the sliced Wasserstein kernel picks up on, and is able to leverage,
discriminatory information that is not contained in the input distributions' marginals.

