In the second scenario, in which the rotation angles are drawn from
a uniform distribution over the interval $(0, \pi/2)$,
the advantage of the sliced Wasserstein kernel relative to the other approaches
is even more pronounced, as expected; 
see  Table \ref{tab:results_toyexample2} and Figure \ref{fig:results_toyexample2}.
Indeed, the three Wasserstein kernels do not outperform the baselines.
The sliced Wasserstein kernel, by contrast, 
is clearly able to pick up on some signal in the input distributions that is
not restricted to the marginals.

