The $R^2$ values, shown in 
Table \ref{tab:results_toyexampleR2} and Figure \ref{fig:results_toyexampleR2},
tell the same story:
in Scenario 1, the Wasserstein kernels substantially outperform their baselines
but they are narrowly outperformed by the sliced Wasserstein kernel;
in Scenario 2, the Wasserstein kernels cannot be used to reliably predict the
outcome, whereas the sliced Wasserstein kernel does a reasonable job,
achieving a mean $R^2$ of $0.74$.

